MIKEINGLE@delphi.com (Mike Ingle) writes:
>passphrase search. The key is just the md5 of the passphrase, and the
>key check bytes are the first 32 bits of a double md5. This allows you
>to check passphrases very quickly.

Why just 32 bits? Up that to 64 and you are already beyond almost
anything possible today.  That's a lot better than relying on speed or
memory size of the encryption. Any 32 bit password no matter how
generated will be weak against brute force.
